{"key":"processedPost-12978696","value":{"id":12978696,"first":12978524,"last":12979342,"when":1280544565,"utime":"07/31/10 05:49 AM","content":"With that much substrate, cooling is going to be the concern, not heating, especially once the bulk substrates begin to colonize.&nbsp; That's enough to heat up a small bedroom to the point you'll need to keep a window open in winter, or run AC in summer to prevent overheating.&nbsp; In addition, the CO2 level would be high enough to be dangerous to sleep in the same room.&nbsp; Keep that in mind.<br /><br />I keep around 1000 large filter patch bags colonizing in a room barely large enough to hold them all, and even with a window wide open in -30F temperatures, I use no supplemental heat to keep it between 65F-75F.&nbsp; CO2 levels run about 12,000 ppm with that same window wide open too.<br />RR","title":"Re: incubation for 80 quart jars","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}